r) |last2=Sfeir |first2=Antoine |title=The Columbia world dictionary of Islamism |year=2007 |publisher=Columbia University Press |location= |isbn=978-0231146401 |page=430 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rNrMilgHKKEC |accessdate=30 July 2011 |ref=harv }}\n* {{Cite book |last1=Roy |first1=Olivier |title=The Failure of Political Islam |publisher=Harvard University Press |year=1994 |url=https://archive.org/details/failureofpolitic00royo |url-access=registration |quote=The Failure of Political Islam muslim world league. |accessdate=2 April 2015 |ref=ORFPI1994|isbn=978-0674291416 }}\n* {{Cite journal |last=Sikand |first=Yoginder |year=1998 |title=The Origins and Growth of the Tablighi Jamaat in Britain |journal=Islam and Christian-Muslim Relations |volume=9 |issue=2 |pages=171\u201392 |doi=10.1080/09596419808721147 }}\n* {{Cite book |last=Sikand |first=Yoginder |year=2002 |title=The Origins and Development of the Tablighi Jama'at (1920s\u20131990s): A cross cultural comparative study |location=New Delhi|publisher=Orient Longman |isbn=978-8125022985 }}\n* {{Cite journal |last=Stern |first=Jessica |title=Pakistan's Jihad Culture. |journal=Foreign Affairs |volume=79 |issue=6 |pages=115\u201326 |year=2000 |url=https://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/asia/2000-11-01/pakistans-jihad-culture |doi=10.2307/20049971 |jstor=20049971 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.delhimarkaz.com/?m=1/ Tablighi Jamaat Official Website]\n\n{{IslamismSA|state=collapse}}\n\n{{Coord|31|15|25|N|74|13|22|E|display=title|region:PK_type:city(31592)_source:dewiki}}\n\n{{good article}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1927 establishments in India]]\n[[Category:Tablighi Jamaat|*]]\n[[Category:Islamic organisations based in India]]\n[[Category:Sunni Islamist groups]]\n[[Category:Islamic organizations established in 1926]]\n[[Category:Deobandi]]\n", "name_user": "Attar SIDDIQUE", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(There are no any terrorist connection.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tablighi_Jamaat"}
{"title_page": "Bank Hall Colliery", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n[[File:Bank Hall Park - geograph.org.uk - 675291.jpg|thumb|right|240px|Monument in Bank Hall Park.]]\n\n'''Bank Hall Colliery''' was a coal mine on the [[Burnley Coalfield]] in [[Burnley]], Lancashire near the [[Leeds and Liverpool Canal]]. Sunk in the late 1860s, it was the town's largest and deepest pit and had a life of more than 100 years.\n\nThe Rev. John Hargreaves (1732-1812), had purchased the Bank Hall estate\u2014previously called Bank Top\u2014by 1796. He entered the local [[coal industry]] through marriage in 1755 and in 1797 he acquired the lease-holds for most of the [[mineral rights]] in the area. After his death, the company adopted the name 'The Executors of John Hargreaves'. His nephew, Colonel John Hargreaves (1775-1834) continued the business until his death. His son had died young, and the property, including Bank Hall and Ormerod Hall in [[Cliviger]], was divided between two daughters. The younger, Charlotte Anne, had married General Sir [[James Yorke Scarlett]], a hero of the [[Battle of Balaclava]], but the couple produced no offspring. The elder, Eleanor Mary, married the Rev. William Thursby and thus the company came under the control of the [[Thursby baronets|Thursby family]].{{sfn|Nadin|1997|p=9|ps=none}}{{sfn|Farrer|Brownbill|1911|p=445|ps=none}} The Bank Hall estate covered a greater area than the later coal mine, with the hall itself located on the southwest side of the canal next to Colne Road.<ref name=\"NLS map\">{{cite web |title=OS 25 inch |url=https://maps.nls.uk/geo/explore/#zoom=16&lat=53.7970&lon=-2.2353&layers=168&b=1 |website=maps.nls.uk |publisher=National Library of Scotland |date=1892\u20131914}}</ref> Its grounds on the [[River Brun]], today make up part of [[Thompson Park (Burnley)|Thompson Park]].<ref>{{NHLE |num=1001496 |desc=Thompson Park, Burnley |access-date=10 November 2019}}</ref> The estate also presumably covered the site of [[Queens Park, Burnley|Queen's Park]]\u2014southeast of the mine\u2014which was donated to the Burnley Corporation by Sir John Hardy Thursby in 1888, for the purpose of creating the first public park in the town.<ref>{{NHLE |num=1001539 |desc=Queens Park, Burnley |access-date=10 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nBank Hall Colliery's first shafts were sunk to the Arley mine{{efn|In this part of Lancashire a coal seam is referred to as a mine and the [[coal mine]] as a colliery or pit.}} at a depth of 287 yards by Executors of John Hargreaves between 1865 and 1869. The four feet thick seam was worked until 1925. The King mine was worked between 1905 and 1925, and the Dandy (or Upper Arley) mine from 1910 to 1935.<ref name=\"BHC\">{{citation |title=Bank Hall Colliery |publisher=Northern Mine Research Society|url=https://www.nmrs.org.uk/mines-map/coal-mining-in-the-british-isles/lancashire-coalfield/the-burnley-coalfield/bank-hall-colliery/|accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref> No. 3 shaft was sunk to the Dandy mine in 1903 and became known as the Dandy Pit.<ref name =\"LT\">{{cite news |last=Johnson |first=Gill |date=3 February 2011 |title=Historian digs into past of Burnley town\u2019s biggest pit |url=http://www.lancashiretelegraph.co.uk/news/8832045.Historian_digs_into_past_of_Burnley_town___s_biggest_pit/|work=Lancashire Telegraph |access-date=23 March 2018 }}</ref>\nNo.4 shaft was sunk to the Union mine, which had been formed by the merger of the Upper Foot and true Lower Mountain mines. Production from the Union mine started in 1915 and became the pit's the major source of coal.<ref name=\"BHC\"/> The fourth shaft at 1,500 feet was the deepest in the coalfield.<ref name =\"LT\"/>\n\nWorsley Mesnes Ironworks in Wigan built a twin horizontal winding engine with 26 inch cylinders for No. 1 shaft in 1912. Its 18 foot drum could wind up to 1,554 feet. [[Yates & Thom]] of Blackburn built No. 4 shaft's cross compound horizontal engine in 1914. It had 38 inch and 60 inch cylinders, a 19 feet drum and could wind to 1,464 feet. [[Walker Brothers (Wigan)|Walker Brothers]] of Wigan supplied a steam fan engine with a 5 feet diameter fly wheel.\n{{sfn|Ashmore|1969|p=251}}\n\nThe colliery was taken over by the [[National Coal Board]] (NCB) on 1 January 1947 and significant investments were made. Haulage roads were made for battery locomotives, which pulled five-ton mine cars and the pit botton at No.4 Shaft  was modernised.<ref name=\"BHC\"/>\n\nThe Union mine proved to be gassy and ignitions of [[firedamp]] were caused by sparks made when mechanised cutter picks hit [[coal ball]]s containing nodules of [[Pyrite|iron pyrites]]. The problems led to the NCB stopping the last coal face working in January 1971 and closed the pit on 17 April. Salvage work was completed and the site cleared in 1972.<ref name=\"BHC\"/>{{sfn|Davies|2010|p=148}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Hapton Valley Colliery]]\n*[[List of collieries in Lancashire since 1854#Burnley area|Collieries in the Burnley area since 1854]]\n*[[Glossary of coal mining terminology]]\n\n==References==\n=== Notes ===\n{{notelist|notes=}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|30em|refs=}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{citation|last=Ashmore|first=Owen|title=Industrial Archaeology of Lancashire|publisher=David & Charles|year=1969|isbn=0715343394|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/theindustrialarch0000unse}}\n*{{citation |last=Davies |first=Alan|title=Coal Mining in Lancashire & Cheshire|publisher=Amberley|year=2010|isbn=978-1-84868-488-1}}\n*{{citation |last=Nadin |first=Jack |title=British Mining No. 58 The Coal Mines of East-Lancashire |publisher=Northern Mine Research Society |year=1997 |isbn=0901450480}} \n*{{citation |editor-last1=Farrer |editor-first1=William |editor-last2=Brownbill |editor-first2=John |title=The Victoria History of the County of Lancaster Vol 6 |publisher=[[Victoria County History]] - Constable & Co |year=1911 |url=https://www.archive.org/details/cu31924088434620 |p=445 |oclc=270761418}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{coord| 53.798| -2.235|region:GB_type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n{{Borough of Burnley culture|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Coal mines in Lancashire]]\n[[Category:Mining in Lancashire]]\n[[Category:Underground mines in England]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Burnley]]\n[[Category:History of Burnley Borough]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n[[File:Bank Hall Park - geograph.org.uk - 675291.jpg|thumb|right|240px|Monument in Bank Hall Park.]]\n\n'''Bank Hall Colliery''' was a coal mine on the [[Burnley Coalfield]] in [[Burnley]], Lancashire near the [[Leeds and Liverpool Canal]]. Sunk in the late 1860s, it was the town's largest and deepest pit and had a life of more than 100 years.\n\nThe Rev. John Hargreaves (1732-1812), had purchased the Bank Hall estate\u2014previously called Bank Top\u2014by 1796. He entered the local [[coal industry]] through marriage in 1755 and in 1797 he acquired the lease-holds for most of the [[mineral rights]] in the area. After his death, the company adopted the name 'The Executors of John Hargreaves'. His nephew, Colonel John Hargreaves (1775-1834) continued the business until his death. His son had died young, and the property, including Bank Hall and Ormerod Hall in [[Cliviger]], was divided between two daughters. The younger, Charlotte Anne, had married General Sir [[James Yorke Scarlett]], a hero of the [[Battle of Balaclava]], but the couple produced no offspring. The elder, Eleanor Mary, married the Rev. William Thursby and thus the company came under the control of the [[Thursby baronets|Thursby family]].{{sfn|Nadin|1997|p=9|ps=none}}{{sfn|Farrer|Brownbill|1911|p=445|ps=none}} The Bank Hall estate covered a greater area than the later coal mine, with the hall itself located on the southwest side of the canal next to Colne Road.<ref name=\"NLS map\">{{cite web |title=OS 25 inch |url=https://maps.nls.uk/geo/explore/#zoom=16&lat=53.7970&lon=-2.2353&layers=168&b=1 |website=maps.nls.uk |publisher=National Library of Scotland |date=1892\u20131914}}</ref> Its grounds on the [[River Brun]], today make up part of [[Thompson Park (Burnley)|Thompson Park]].<ref>{{NHLE |num=1001496 |desc=Thompson Park, Burnley |access-date=10 November 2019}}</ref> The estate also presumably covered the site of [[Queens Park, Burnley|Queen's Park]]\u2014southeast of the mine\u2014which was donated to the Burnley Corporation by Sir John Hardy Thursby in 1888, for the purpose of creating the first public park in the town.<ref>{{NHLE |num=1001539 |desc=Queens Park, Burnley |access-date=10 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nBank Hall Colliery's first shafts were sunk to the Arley mine{{efn|In this part of Lancashire a coal seam is referred to as a mine and the [[coal mine]] as a colliery or pit.}} at a depth of 287 yards by Executors of John Hargreaves between 1865 and 1869. The four feet thick seam was worked until 1925. The King mine was worked between 1905 and 1925, and the Dandy (or Upper Arley) mine from 1910 to 1935.<ref name=\"BHC\">{{citation |title=Bank Hall Colliery |publisher=Northern Mine Research Society|url=https://www.nmrs.org.uk/mines-map/coal-mining-in-the-british-isles/lancashire-coalfield/the-burnley-coalfield/bank-hall-colliery/|accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref> No. 3 shaft was sunk to the Dandy mine in 1903 and became known as the Dandy Pit.<ref name =\"LT\">{{cite news |last=Johnson |first=Gill |date=3 February 2011 |title=Historian digs into past of Burnley town\u2019s biggest pit |url=http://www.lancashiretelegraph.co.uk/news/8832045.Historian_digs_into_past_of_Burnley_town___s_biggest_pit/|work=Lancashire Telegraph |access-date=23 March 2018 }}</ref>\nNo.4 shaft was sunk to the Union mine, which had been formed by the merger of the Upper Foot and true Lower Mountain mines. Production from the Union mine started in 1915 and became the pit's the major source of coal.<ref name=\"BHC\"/> The fourth shaft at 1,500 feet was the deepest in the coalfield.<ref name =\"LT\"/>\n\nWorsley Mesnes Ironworks in Wigan built a twin horizontal winding engine with 26 inch cylinders for No. 1 shaft in 1912. Its 18 foot drum could wind up to 1,554 feet. [[Yates and Thom]] of Blackburn built No. 4 shaft's cross compound horizontal engine in 1914. It had 38 inch and 60 inch cylinders, a 19 feet drum and could wind to 1,464 feet. Walker Bros of Wigan supplied a steam fan engine with a 5 feet diameter fly wheel.\n{{sfn|Ashmore|1969|p=251}}\n\nThe colliery was taken over by the [[National Coal Board]] (NCB) on 1 January 1947 and significant investments were made. Haulage roads were made for battery locomotives, which pulled five-ton mine cars and the pit botton at No.4 Shaft  was modernised.<ref name=\"BHC\"/>\n\nThe Union mine proved to be gassy and ignitions of [[firedamp]] were caused by sparks made when mechanised cutter picks hit [[coal ball]]s containing nodules of [[Pyrite|iron pyrites]]. The problems led to the NCB stopping the last coal face working in January 1971 and closed the pit on 17 April. Salvage work was completed and the site cleared in 1972.<ref name=\"BHC\"/>{{sfn|Davies|2010|p=148}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Hapton Valley Colliery]]\n*[[List of collieries in Lancashire since 1854#Burnley area|Collieries in the Burnley area since 1854]]\n*[[Glossary of coal mining terminology]]\n\n==References==\n=== Notes ===\n{{notelist|notes=}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|30em|refs=}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{citation|last=Ashmore|first=Owen|title=Industrial Archaeology of Lancashire|publisher=David & Charles|year=1969|isbn=0715343394|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/theindustrialarch0000unse}}\n*{{citation |last=Davies |first=Alan|title=Coal Mining in Lancashire & Cheshire|publisher=Amberley|year=2010|isbn=978-1-84868-488-1}}\n*{{citation |last=Nadin |first=Jack |title=British Mining No. 58 The Coal Mines of East-Lancashire |publisher=Northern Mine Research Society |year=1997 |isbn=0901