{"title_page": "Nov\u00e9 Sady (\u017d\u010f\u00e1r nad S\u00e1zavou District)", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|name=Nov\u00e9 Sady\n|settlement_type=Municipality\n|image_skyline= Chapel in Nov\u00e9 Sady, \u017d\u010f\u00e1r nad S\u00e1zavou District.JPG\n|image_caption = Chapel in Nov\u00e9 Sady\n|image_shield=\n|image_flag=\n|subdivision_type=Country\n|subdivision_name={{CZE}}\n|subdivision_type1=[[Regions of the Czech Republic|Region]]\n|subdivision_name1=[[Vyso\u010dina Region|Vyso\u010dina]]\n|subdivision_type2=[[Districts of the Czech Republic|District]]\n|subdivision_name2=[[\u017d\u010f\u00e1r nad S\u00e1zavou District|\u017d\u010f\u00e1r nad S\u00e1zavou]]\n|coordinates = {{coord|49|17|28|N|16|11|35|E|region:CZ|display=inline,title}}\n|pushpin_map=Czech Republic|area_total_km2=3.65\n|population_total=188|population_as_of=2006\n|population_density_km2=auto\n|elevation_m=495\n|postal_code_type=Postal&nbsp;code|postal_code=595&nbsp;01\n|website=http://www.novesady.cz\n}}\n\n'''Nov\u00e9 Sady''' is a village and municipality (''[[obec]]'') in [[\u017d\u010f\u00e1r nad S\u00e1zavou District]] in the [[Vyso\u010dina Region]] of the Czech Republic.\n\nThe municipality covers an area of {{convert|3.65|km2|sqmi}}, and has a population of 188 (as at 28&nbsp;August 2006).\n\nNov\u00e9 Sady lies approximately {{convert|36|km|mi|0}} south-east of [[\u017d\u010f\u00e1r nad S\u00e1zavou]], {{convert|46|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} east of [[Jihlava]], and {{convert|156|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} south-east of [[Prague]].\n\nIn 2019, the population of Nov\u00e9 Sady are 113 males and 111 females.\n\n==References==\n*[http://www.czso.cz/lexikon/mos_vdb.nsf/okresy/CZ0615/ Czech Statistical Office: Municipalities of \u017d\u010f\u00e1r nad S\u00e1zavou District]\n\n{{\u017d\u010f\u00e1r nad S\u00e1zavou District}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nove Sady}}\n[[Category:Villages in \u017d\u010f\u00e1r nad S\u00e1zavou District]]\n\n\n{{Vyso\u010dina-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|name=Nov\u00e9 Sady\n|settlement_type=Municipality\n|image_skyline= Chapel in Nov\u00e9 Sady, \u017d\u010f\u00e1r nad S\u00e1zavou District.JPG\n|image_caption = Chapel in Nov\u00e9 Sady\n|image_shield=\n|image_flag=\n|subdivision_type=Country\n|subdivision_name={{CZE}}\n|subdivision_type1=[[Regions of the Czech Republic|Region]]\n|subdivision_name1=[[Vyso\u010dina Region|Vyso\u010dina]]\n|subdivision_type2=[[Districts of the Czech Republic|District]]\n|subdivision_name2=[[\u017d\u010f\u00e1r nad S\u00e1zavou District|\u017d\u010f\u00e1r nad S\u00e1zavou]]\n|coordinates = {{coord|49|17|28|N|16|11|35|E|region:CZ|display=inline,title}}\n|pushpin_map=Czech Republic|area_total_km2=3.65\n|population_total=188|population_as_of=2006\n|population_density_km2=auto\n|elevation_m=495\n|postal_code_type=Postal&nbsp;code|postal_code=595&nbsp;01\n|website=http://www.novesady.cz\n}}\n\n'''Nov\u00e9 Sady''' is a village and municipality (''[[obec]]'') in [[\u017d\u010f\u00e1r nad S\u00e1zavou District]] in the [[Vyso\u010dina Region]] of the Czech Republic.\n\nThe municipality covers an area of {{convert|3.65|km2|sqmi}}, and has a population of 188 (as at 28&nbsp;August 2006).\n\nNov\u00e9 Sady lies approximately {{convert|36|km|mi|0}} south-east of [[\u017d\u010f\u00e1r nad S\u00e1zavou]], {{convert|46|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} east of [[Jihlava]], and {{convert|156|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} south-east of [[Prague]].\n\n==References==\n*[http://www.czso.cz/lexikon/mos_vdb.nsf/okresy/CZ0615/ Czech Statistical Office: Municipalities of \u017d\u010f\u00e1r nad S\u00e1zavou District]\n\n{{\u017d\u010f\u00e1r nad S\u00e1zavou District}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nove Sady}}\n[[Category:Villages in \u017d\u010f\u00e1r nad S\u00e1zavou District]]\n\n\n{{Vyso\u010dina-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Xmin981001", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nov%C3%A9_Sady_(%C5%BD%C4%8F%C3%A1r_nad_S%C3%A1zavou_District)"}
{"title_page": "The Autobiography of Calvin Coolidge", "text_new": "{{Italic title}}\n{{Infobox book\n| name          = The Autobiography of Calvin Coolidge\n| image         = Coolidge Autobiography title page.jpg\n| caption       = Title page, first edition\n| author        = [[Calvin Coolidge]]\n| cover_artist  = \n| country       = United States\n| language      = English\n| subject       = [[Autobiography]]\n| publisher     = [[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan Book Corporation]]\n| pub_date      = 1929 (hardback)\n| pages         = 246\n| isbn          = \n| dewey= \n| congress= \n| oclc= 946864\n| preceded_by   =\n| followed_by   =\n}}\n'''''The Autobiography of Calvin Coolidge''''' is an [[autobiography]] written by former [[United States President]] [[Calvin Coolidge]].  It was published in 1929, shortly after Coolidge left office.\n\nCoolidge's autobiography consisted of about 45,000 words, unusually short in comparison to the era's typical \"long-winded\" biographies and autobiographies.<ref name=PittsburghTerse1929/> It was praised by [[Ray Long]] (editor of [[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|''Cosmopolitan'']] magazine) for describing the complete story of Coolidge's life and \"the complete story of our country during the dramatic years of this generation.\"<ref name=\"sun\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=TkEpAAAAIBAJ&sjid=lGYFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3455,2694671&dq=coolidge+autobiography&hl=en|title=Coolidge's Literary Output is Voluminous|date=April 30, 1929|work=The Lewiston [Maine] Daily Sun|page=11|accessdate=August 8, 2012}}</ref> Coolidge was one of the first U.S. Presidents to write and publish an autobiography. Coolidge's autobiography covers all the notable moments in his life, such as his childhood and youth, Governorship, Presidency, son's death, and retirement. It was criticized by some for being too obvious and not presenting any new information that was previously unknown to the public. However, this trait of the autobiography was not that surprising as no one expected Coolidge to reveal some private government information and secrets in his autobiography (Coolidge was a very private man, despite his happy-going and cheerful public personality image).<ref name=\"times daily\">{{cite news|last=Catton|first=Bruce|title=Coolidge Discreet in Autobiography|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=TiksAAAAIBAJ&sjid=D7oEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2796,5703363&dq=calvin+coolidge+autobiography&hl=en|accessdate=July 31, 2012|newspaper=Times Daily|date=November 22, 1929}}</ref> However, it was also complimented for its succinctness and relative shortness, considering that most autobiographies of the time were much longer. Coolidge's autobiography, in contrast, was about half the size of a novel.<ref name=PittsburghTerse1929>{{cite news|title=Coolidge is Terse in Autobiography|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=zm8bAAAAIBAJ&sjid=_koEAAAAIBAJ&pg=1310,6928984&dq=calvin+coolidge+autobiography&hl=en|accessdate=July 31, 2012|newspaper=The Pittsburgh Press|date=April 30, 1929|agency=The United Press}}</ref> One of the most notable moments in the book was Coolidge's belief that President [[Warren Harding]] would recover (in 1923) and then his surprise and inauguration following Harding's death.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Autobiography of Calvin Coolidge|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=GIlZAAAAIBAJ&sjid=FUkNAAAAIBAJ&pg=1145,4064919&dq=calvin+coolidge+autobiography&hl=en|accessdate=July 31, 2012|newspaper=Rochester Evening Journal|date=February 10, 1933}}</ref>\n\nThe Coolidge autobiography was extremely popular at the time of its publication, as evidenced by the large amount of [[fan mail]] that its author received and by the willingness of many newspapers to publish parts of the autobiography so that much more of the American public could buy it and view it.<ref name=\"post\"/> Coolidge said that he hoped that his autobiography might guide and encourage the young men and women of America.<ref name=\"post\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=KKlRAAAAIBAJ&sjid=6mgDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3505,4914563&dq=coolidge+autobiography&hl=en|title=Coolidge Now Talks of Dogs, His Life Story, Home Plans|last=Fitch|first=Geraldine|date=November 12, 1929|work=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|page=2|accessdate=August 8, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of United States Presidential autobiographies]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Calvin Coolidge}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Autobiography of Calvin Coolidge, The}}\n[[Category:1929 non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:Political autobiographies]]\n[[Category:American autobiographies]]\n[[Category:Calvin Coolidge]]\n[[Category:Books written by Presidents of the United States]]\n\n\n{{US-poli-bio-book-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Italic title}}\n{{Infobox book\n| name          = The Autobiography of Calvin Coolidge\n| image         = Coolidge Autobiography title page.jpg\n| caption       = Title page, first edition\n| author        = [[Calvin Coolidge]]\n| cover_artist  = \n| country       = United States\n| language      = English\n| subject       = [[Autobiography]]\n| publisher     = [[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan Book Corporation]]\n| pub_date      = 1929 (hardback)\n| pages         = 246\n| isbn          = \n| dewey= \n| congress= \n| oclc= 946864\n| preceded_by   =\n| followed_by   =\n}}\n'''''The Autobiography of Calvin Coolidge''''' is an [[autobiography]] written by former [[United States President]] [[Calvin Coolidge]].  It was published in 1929, shortly after Coolidge left office.\n\nCoolidge's autobiography consisted of about 45,000 words, unusually short in comparison to the era's typical \"long-winded\" biographies and autobiographies.<ref name=PittsburghTerse1929/> It was praised by [[Ray Long]] (editor of [[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|''Cosmopolitan'']] magazine) for describing the complete story of Coolidge's life and \"the complete story of our country during the dramatic years of this generation.\"<ref name=\"sun\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=TkEpAAAAIBAJ&sjid=lGYFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3455,2694671&dq=coolidge+autobiography&hl=en|title=Coolidge's Literary Output is Voluminous|date=April 30, 1929|work=The Lewiston [Maine] Daily Sun|page=11|accessdate=August 8, 2012}}</ref> Coolidge was one of the first U.S. Presidents to write and publish an autobiography. Coolidge's autobiography covers all the notable moments in his life, such as his childhood and youth, Governorship, Presidency, son's death, and retirement. It was criticized by some for being too obvious and not presenting any new information that was previously unknown to the public. However, this trait of the autobiography was not that surprising as no one expected Coolidge to reveal some private government information and secrets in his autobiography (Coolidge was a very private man, despite his happy-going and cheerful public personality image).<ref name=\"times daily\">{{cite news|last=Catton|first=Bruce|title=Coolidge Discreet in Autobiography|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=TiksAAAAIBAJ&sjid=D7oEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2796,5703363&dq=calvin+coolidge+autobiography&hl=en|accessdate=July 31, 2012|newspaper=Times Daily|date=November 22, 1929}}</ref> However, it was also complimented for its succinctness and relative shortness, considering that most autobiographies of the time were much longer. Coolidge's autobiography, in contrast, was about half the size of a novel.<ref name=PittsburghTerse1929>{{cite news|title=Coolidge is Terse in Autobiography|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=zm8bAAAAIBAJ&sjid=_koEAAAAIBAJ&pg=1310,6928984&dq=calvin+coolidge+autobiography&hl=en|accessdate=July 31, 2012|newspaper=The Pittsburgh Press|date=April 30, 1929|agency=The United Press}}</ref> One of the most notable moments in the book was Coolidge's belief that President [[Warren Harding]] would recover (in 1923) and then his surprise and inauguration following Harding's death.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Autobiography of Calvin Coolidge|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=GIlZAAAAIBAJ&sjid=FUkNAAAAIBAJ&pg=1145,4064919&dq=calvin+coolidge+autobiography&hl=en|accessdate=July 31, 2012|newspaper=Rochester Evening Journal|date=February 10, 1933}}</ref>\n\nThe Coolidge autobiography was extremely popular at the time of its publication, as evidenced by the large amount of [[fan mail]] that its author received and by the willingness of many newspapers to publish parts of the autobiography so that much more of the American public could buy it and view it.<ref name=\"post\"/> Coolidge said that he hoped that his autobiography might guide and encourage the young men and women of America.<ref name=\"post\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=KKlRAAAAIBAJ&sjid=6mgDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3505,4914563&dq=coolidge+autobiography&hl=en|title=Coolidge Now Talks of Dogs, His Life Story, Home Plans|last=Fitch|first=Geraldine|date=November 12, 1929|work=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|page=2|accessdate=August 8, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of United States Presidential autobiographies]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Calvin Coolidge}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Autobiography of Calvin Coolidge, The}}\n[[Category:1929 books]]\n[[Category:Political autobiographies]]\n[[Category:American autobiographies]]\n[[Category:Calvin Coolidge]]\n[[Category:Books written by Presidents of the United States]]\n\n\n{{US-poli-bio-book-stub}}\n", "name_user": "I grieve in stereo", "label": "safe", "comment": "Moving fromCategory:1929 bookstoCategory:1929 non-fiction booksusingCat-a-lot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Autobiography_of_Calvin_Coolidge"}
